description:
The CustomIndicator and CustomItem components for SelectInput are copy-pasted identically in two files:

**src/components/QuizStep.tsx lines 21-41:**
```tsx
function CustomIndicator({ isSelected }: { isSelected?: boolean }) {
  return (
    <Text color={isSelected ? COLORS.amber : COLORS.gray}>
      {isSelected ? "> " : "  "}
    </Text>
  );
}

function CustomItem({ isSelected, label }: { isSelected?: boolean; label: string }) {
  return (
    <Text color={isSelected ? COLORS.amber : COLORS.gray} bold={isSelected}>
      {label}
    </Text>
  );
}
```

**src/screens/InfiniteMode.tsx lines 58-78:** Identical code.

This is a visual consistency risk: if someone updates the select styling in one place (e.g., changes the indicator character from ">" to something else, or changes the selected color), the other won't follow.

**Fix:** Extract CustomIndicator and CustomItem into a shared component file (e.g., \`src/components/SelectStyles.tsx\`) and import in both locations. This ensures select inputs look identical everywhere.

Stars are rendered with two separate implementations that could drift apart:

**Debrief.tsx lines 17-21 + 62-64:**
```tsx
const STAR_FILLED = "\u2605";
const STAR_EMPTY = "\u2606";
function renderStars(stars: 1 | 2 | 3): string {
  return STAR_FILLED.repeat(stars) + STAR_EMPTY.repeat(3 - stars);
}
// ...
const starString =
  STAR_FILLED.repeat(starsRevealed) + STAR_EMPTY.repeat(3 - starsRevealed);
```
Note: \`renderStars\` is defined but never called ‚Äî the inline code on lines 62-64 is used instead. Dead code.

**MissionMap.tsx lines 290-294:**
```tsx
function starString(rating: number): string {
  const filled = "\u2605";
  const empty = "\u2606";
  return filled.repeat(rating) + empty.repeat(3 - rating);
}
```

Both use the same Unicode characters but define them independently. Additionally, the Debrief has an unused \`renderStars\` function that was presumably replaced by the inline version for the animation effect.

**Color difference:**
- MissionMap renders stars in \`COLORS.gold\` (line 270)
- Debrief renders stars in \`COLORS.gold\` (line 88)
These match, which is good.

**Fix:**
1. Delete the unused \`renderStars\` function and \`STAR_FILLED\`/\`STAR_EMPTY\` constants from Debrief.tsx (or use them)
2. Extract the star-rendering logic to a shared utility or component (e.g., \`src/components/Stars.tsx\` or a helper in constants) so both screens use the same code
